Scripts

When using R, it’s important that you are performing all operations by writing scripts of code to be run in R, rather than coding directly into the Console. Scripts allow you to save and modify your code as you move along, as well as go back to it later. You can open a script under File - New File - New R Script. Type your code directly into the script, and run individual lines of code either by clicking “Run” at the top of the script, or using the shortcut Cmd-Enter (Mac) / Ctrl-Enter (Windows).

You can annotate your code with information that helps you to understand each line by commenting after the symbol # in a code line.

1+1 #this is a simple way to annotate; anything written after # will not be included in the code run
## [1] 2

Types of data

There are many different types of data in R: values, vectors, matrices, dataframes, rasters, and more.

Before starting work in R, it can be useful to clear your environment so that any previous work sessions do not interfere with your current operations.

object1 = data.frame()
rm(list=ls())

Objects

The simplest are objects - you can assign values to objects easily and perform calculations.

x <- 6
2*x + 3
## [1] 15
y <- 2
y^2
## [1] 4

Vectors

You can also create vectors using the combine function c() A vector is a sequence of data that are of the same type

x <- c(1,3,4,2,4,6,5) # integers or numerals
x
## [1] 1 3 4 2 4 6 5
class(x)
## [1] "numeric"
y <- c("a", "b", "c", "d") # characters
y
## [1] "a" "b" "c" "d"
class(y)
## [1] "character"

Indexing vectors

Within a vector, you can extract individual values based on their index, for example:

x[1] #first value
x[3] #third value

y[2]
y[4]
## [1] 1
## [1] 4
## [1] "b"
## [1] "d"

To extract multiple values, you can either extract consecutive values using the colon, or by combining indices with c()

x
x[2:5] #2nd, 3rd, 4th, and 5th values
x[c(2,4,7)] #2nd, 4th, and 7th values
## [1] 1 3 4 2 4 6 5
## [1] 3 4 2 4
## [1] 3 2 5

Matrices

The next data type is matrices, which are 2-dimensional layouts of data. We can easily create these from a vector:

vector.x <- c(4,7,2,8,5,3,8,0,6,4,2,7,6,9,3,1)
matrix.x <- matrix(vector.x,4,4) #4 rows, 4 columns
matrix.x2 <- matrix(vector.x,2,8) #2 rows, 8 columns

When specifying the number of rows and columns in R, rows come first.

matrix.x[1,3] # [ROW,COLUMN]
## [1] 6

In the above code, R fills out the matrix of specified dimensions by column (default), so that in the above, a 4x4 matrix would contain, from top to bottom, the values 4,7,2,8 in the first column. If you’d like to fill out each row in order rather than column, that change is easily made.

matrix.x3 <- matrix(vector.x,4,4,byrow=TRUE)


head(matrix.x) #filled out by column
##      [,1] [,2] [,3] [,4]
## [1,]    4    5    6    6
## [2,]    7    3    4    9
## [3,]    2    8    2    3
## [4,]    8    0    7    1
head(matrix.x3) #filled out by row
##      [,1] [,2] [,3] [,4]
## [1,]    4    7    2    8
## [2,]    5    3    8    0
## [3,]    6    4    2    7
## [4,]    6    9    3    1

Data Frames

When multiple columns or vectors of data are combined, this is called a dataframe (think of data in spreadsheet form). Dataframes can be created manually or loaded into R using a spreadsheet in .csv format (more on this later).

Writing Dataframes

First - We will write a simple dataset with mock catch data for a hypothetical fish species for the years 2010-2014.

catchdata <- data.frame("year" = 2010:2014, "catch" = c(5000,5200,7100,4900,5150))
# year, catch = columns
head(catchdata)
##   year catch
## 1 2010  5000
## 2 2011  5200
## 3 2012  7100
## 4 2013  4900
## 5 2014  5150

Merging data

Dataframes can be merged using the row bind rbind() function.

# write another dataframe with same column names
catchdata2 <- data.frame("year"=c(2015:2019),  "catch"=c(4100,5700,3850,5500,4900))
head(catchdata2)
##   year catch
## 1 2015  4100
## 2 2016  5700
## 3 2017  3850
## 4 2018  5500
## 5 2019  4900
alldata <- rbind(catchdata, catchdata2)

You can also combine columns of data using the column bind cbind() function.

Saving dataframes

We can now save our new master dataframe as a .csv file as well, using the write.csv() command.

write.csv(alldata, "alldata.csv")

Files will be saved to your working directory

Setting a working directory and reading .csv files

Setting a working directory

The working directory is the directory on your computer where R will retrieve and store data as well as save outputs such as plots and spreadsheets.

For this class, you should maintain a consistent file structure such that you can always code it. For example, on your local desktop, you might start a folder called “Fisheries Management”, with subfolders such as “Data”, “Figures”, “Scripts”, etc., so that you can easily tell R where to save and retrieve files. There are three ways to set your working directory, and we’ll cover all three, but it’s always best to code it (Option 3).

Using Packages

R is an open source software, which means that users can create packages of functions for use by others. There are thousands of R packages available for different applications, including packages which are used specifically for analyzing fisheries data.

There are also several packages which are commonly used in many R operations, such as data management and plotting. We are going to install tidyverse, which is a collection of several frequently used packages including ggplot, dplyr, and tidyr. To install packages, there are several options - again, coding is the best.

  1. Code it using install.packages("tidyverse")

  2. In the menu bar, select “Tools” and then “Install Packages…”. Open source packages are found on the CRAN repository. Search for “tidyverse”.

  3. In the inset window at the bottom right, select the “Packages” tab and then click “Install”. Search for “tidyverse” within the CRAN repository.

Subsetting Dataframes

We learned earlier to merge dataframes; alternatively, you can subset dataframes into smaller dataframes using the subset() function. Subset allows us to select rows from the dataframe where the value from a specific column meets a certain condition - for example, we can subset the larger dataframe to only include the years after 1980.

usa_landings_post1980 <- subset(usa_landings, year>1980) # saves the subset as a new dataframe
head(usa_landings_post1980)
##    year   catch country
## 32 1981 3701137     USA
## 33 1982 3952683     USA
## 34 1983 4152983     USA
## 35 1984 4721775     USA
## 36 1985 4719868     USA
## 37 1986 4880950     USA

The use of operators such as >, =, !, etc. is extremely important in R, particularly when subsetting. A list of operators:

x <- 5
y <- 10
x < y # less than
x <= y # less than or equal to
x > y # greater than
x >= y # greater than or equal to
x == y # is equal to
x != y #is not equal to
!x # is not x
x|y # x OR y
x&y # x AND y
isTRUE(x) # test if X is TRUE
isTRUE(TRUE)

Examples

# Tip: run these functions one at a time instead of the whole chunk at once 
subset(usa_landings, year==2007) #only 2007 data
subset(usa_landings, year!=2007) #everything EXCEPT the year 2007
subset(usa_landings, catch>=3000000) #years where catch was greater than or equal to 3 million tons
subset(usa_landings, year<1980 | year>=1990) #All years before 1980 and after 1989
subset(usa_landings, year>1980 & catch>=5000000) # All years after 1980 where catch was 5 million tons or greater

Plotting in Base R

The Base R packages allow for some basic plotting through the plot() function. The default plot type will be a scatter plot. To plot the catches from our usa_landings dataframe, we can use the following code:

plot(catch~year, data=usa_landings)

We can also code this as follows with the same result, using the $ operator. The $ operator allows us to specify a column from a dataframe such as usa_landings, so:

plot(usa_landings$catch~usa_landings$year)

gives the same result as above.

NOTE: The $ operator defines columns in a dataframe and can be very useful.

Now, see what else the plot function can do with ?plot

?plot
## Help on topic 'plot' was found in the following packages:
## 
##   Package               Library
##   graphics              /usr/lib/R/library
##   base                  /usr/lib/R/library
## 
##

This works for all functions. We can see in this case that we can change the plot style; for example, we can create the same plot as a line plot

plot(catch~year, data=usa_landings, type="l", col='red')

Plotting in ggplot

ggplot is a commonly used package for plotting as it is highly customizable. Plots are created by defining geom objects, such as points, lines, or polygons. There are numerous ggplot guides available which discuss how different plot components can be customized.

ggplot(usa_landings) +
  geom_line(aes(x=year, y=catch)) + #creates the line plot
  geom_point(aes(x=year, y=catch), color="red") + #adds the red points 
  ylab("Catch (Tons)") + #y axis title
  xlab("Year") + #x axis title
  ggtitle("United States Annual Landings") #main plot title

ggplot allows you to customize axes, labels, legends, line and shape styles, and most any other aspect of the plot you may want to modify. Look online at the available guides for additional information on plotting in ggplot.

bookdown_ggplot

Using packages and functions to access data

Some packages are designed to allow the user to access databases and data through R for ease of analysis. Let’s take a look at rfisheries – you might need to install this with install.packages("rfisheries") in the console.

There are many ways to look at the data; first, let’s look at all reported catch in the FAO dataset. Here, we create a dataframe annual.landings with total annual landings for each year, using the rfisheries package.

# install.packages('rfisheries')
library(rfisheries)
annual.landings = of_landings()
plot(data=annual.landings, catch~year, type='l')

There are many options to produce data from of_landings, which we can see by looking at the help documents

?of_landings

Next let’s look at a specific country. We first need to determine the country code for the country we want to analyze - we will use the United States.

countrycodes=of_country_codes() # can view this to see available country codes
annual.landings.usa = of_landings(country="USA")
plot(data=annual.landings.usa, catch~year, type='l')

We can also look at specific species - first, we need to identify the species code.

species=rfisheries::of_species_codes()
head(species)
##          scientific_name   taxocode a3_code isscaap            english_name
## 1     Petromyzon marinus 1020100101     LAU      25             Sea lamprey
## 2   Lampetra fluviatilis 1020100201     LAR      25           River lamprey
## 3    Lampetra tridentata 1020100202     LAO      25         Pacific lamprey
## 4 Ichthyomyzon unicuspis 1020100401     LAY      25          Silver lamprey
## 5    Eudontomyzon mariae 1020100501     LAF      25 Ukrainian brook lamprey
## 6      Geotria australis 1020100701     LAE      25         Pouched lamprey

This returns a very long list. We can use the tools in tidyverse to filter this data out to a more usable format. Let’s say we are interested in landings of different tuna species. The following code will search the species dataframe for a partial match of the word “tuna” in the english_name column.

tuna = species %>%
  filter(str_detect(english_name %>% tolower(), pattern = "tuna"))
head(tuna)
##            scientific_name      taxocode a3_code isscaap
## 1      Gymnosarda unicolor    1750101202     DOT      36
## 2            Auxis thazard    1750102301     FRI      36
## 3             Auxis rochei    1750102303     BLT      36
## 4 Auxis thazard, A. rochei 17501023XX018     FRZ      36
## 5       Katsuwonus pelamis    1750102501     SKJ      36
## 6          Thunnus thynnus    1750102601     BFT      36
##               english_name
## 1            Dogtooth tuna
## 2             Frigate tuna
## 3              Bullet tuna
## 4 Frigate and bullet tunas
## 5            Skipjack tuna
## 6    Atlantic bluefin tuna

Some notes on the above code:
- %>% is called a pipe, and is an operator within the pacakge dplyr. It is used to chain commands together. The above code takes the dataframe species and then filters it for rows that have a partial match for the word “tuna”.
- filter() usually requires a full text match. The str_detect() function allows us to use it for a partial match, so that we get all species of tuna.
- Because R is case-sensitive, we use the tolower() command before searching.

The result is a dataframe called tuna which has the common name, scientific name, and species code for each species of tuna in the database. Let’s look at bigeye tuna - their code is “BET”. To isolate landings of bigeye tuna, we use the following code.

BET_landings = of_landings(species="BET")
ggplot(BET_landings) +
  geom_line(aes(x=year, y=catch), col="green") +
  ylab("Annual Catch (Tons)")+
  xlab("Year")+
  ggtitle("Bigeye Tuna Landings")

Let’s repeat the process for blue sharks.

blueshark = species %>%
  filter(str_detect(english_name %>% tolower(), pattern = "blue shark"))
head(blueshark)

Blue sharks code is “BSH”

BSH_landings = rfisheries::of_landings(species="BSH")
ggplot(BSH_landings) +
  geom_line(aes(x=year, y=catch), col="blue") +
  ylab("Annual Catch (Tons)")+
  xlab("Year")+
  ggtitle("Blue Shark Landings")

We can plot landings for the same two species together:

plot(data=BET_landings, catch~year, type="l", col="green")
lines(data=BSH_landings, catch~year, col="blue", lty=2) #lty=2 is a dashed line
legend("topleft", legend=c("Bigeye Tuna", "Blue Shark"), 
       lty=c(1,2), col=c("green","blue"))

We can combine the two dataframes into one

landings=rbind(BET_landings,BSH_landings)

And plot in ggplot, using the column “species” as the group in order to differentiate between the data points.

ggplot(landings, aes(x=year, y=catch, group=species)) +
  geom_line(aes(color=species)) +
  scale_color_manual(values=c("green", "blue")) +
  ylab("Catch (Tons)") +
  xlab("Year") +
  ggtitle("Annual Landings") +
  labs(color="Species")
